✦ To understand the project, you only need to look at 3 key files. Think of it as a "Body, Brain, and Judge" system.

  1. The Brain: src/core/logic/agent.js
  Look here to understand the "Conversation Flow."
  This is the orchestrator. It decides what happens next.
   * extractSkills(): This is the starting point. It takes the JD and Resume, sends them to the AI, and gets back a list of 6 skills to test.
   * getNextQuestion(): This is the most important logic. Look for the line:
      const shouldProbe = log.prelimScore <= 3 && log.extraProbes < 1;
       * If the AI gives the user a low score (3 or less), the Brain says: "Wait, don't move to the next skill yet. Ask a follow-up (Probe) question."
       * If the score is high (4 or 5), it says: "They know their stuff, skip to the next skill." This is why it's faster now.

  2. The Judge: src/core/logic/scoring.js
  Look here to understand the "Scoring Formula."
  We don't just trust the AI blindly. We use this file to "audit" the AI's score.
   * calculateSkillScore(): This is the "Formula."
       * It takes the prelimScore (what the AI thinks).
       * It checks hadProbe (did we have to ask a follow-up?).
       * The Logic: If a user failed the first question but nailed the hard follow-up, this engine boosts their score. If they failed both, it locks them
         into a "Gap" verdict.
       * This ensures the final verdict is based on evidence, not just a single AI guess.

  3. The Memory: src/core/logic/state.js
  Look here to understand "The Data."
  In many apps, data is scattered everywhere. Here, we follow the Sovereign Rule: data lives only in one place.
   * state object: Look at the blankState function. It shows you exactly what the app "remembers" at any time (the API key, the skills found, the interview
     transcript, etc.).
   * Because all data is here, if you want to add a "Save PDF" feature later, you only need to look at this one file to see where the data is stored.

